180	\section{Sheaf cohomology with $k$-module coefficients}
181	\label{sec:HModule}
182	
183	The abstract cohomology API is formulated for sheaves of abelian groups. To obtain a $k$-vector-space structure on $H^n(C, \mathcal O_C)$, we build a parallel sheaf cohomology valued in $k$-modules. The sheaf category of $k$-modules already has $\Ext$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}), and $\Ext$ groups in any $k$-linear abelian category carry a canonical $k$-module structure.
184	
185	\begin{definition}\leanok
186	[Sheaf cohomology with $k$-module coefficients]
187	  \label{def:Scheme_HModule}
188	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule}
189	  \uses{thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK, thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}
190	  Let $k$ be a field, $C$ a Grothendieck site admitting sheafification of $k$-modules and $\Ext$. For a sheaf $F$ of $k$-modules and $n \in \mathbb N$, define the $k$-module-valued sheaf cohomology
191	  \[
192	    H^n_{\Module}(F) \;:=\; \Ext^n\bigl(\text{constant sheaf at }k,\; F\bigr).
193	  \]
194	  This automatically carries a $k$-module structure.
195	\end{definition}
196	
197	\begin{remark}[Lean implementation]
198	  The declaration uses a reducible wrapper (`abbrev` rather than `def`) so that instance synthesis sees through to the underlying $\Ext$ group and finds both the $k$-module and abelian-group structures automatically. Under a non-reducible wrapper, `Module.finrank` would fail to typecheck.
199	\end{remark}
200	
201	\section{The $H^0$ algebraic bridge}
202	\label{sec:HModule_zero}
203	
204	After Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule} the cohomology groups $H^n_{\Module}(F)$ are well-defined and carry the canonical $k$-module structure. The next algebraic preliminary is the identification of the degree-zero piece $H^0_{\Module}(F)$ with a $\Hom$ group: the bridge from sheaf cohomology to representable Hom-functors.
205	
206	\begin{definition}\leanok
207	[$H^0$ as a $k$-linear Hom group]
208	  \label{def:Scheme_HModule_zero_linearEquiv}
209	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule_zero_linearEquiv}
210	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule, thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK, thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}
211	  Let $k$ be a field, $C$ a Grothendieck site admitting sheafification of $k$-modules and $\Ext$, and $F$ a sheaf of $k$-modules. Then there is a canonical $k$-linear equivalence
212	  \[
213	    H^0_{\Module}(F) \;\simeq_k\; \Hom(\text{constant sheaf at }k,\; F).
214	  \]
215	\end{definition}
216	
217	\begin{proof}
218	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule}
219	  \leanok
220	  Direct from Mathlib's $H^0$ bridge in any $k$-linear abelian category, applied to the sheaf category of $k$-modules. The $k$-linear enrichment is auto-inferable from the sheafification hypothesis.
221	\end{proof}
222	
223	\begin{remark}[Choice of linear equivalence]
224	  Mathlib provides three flavours of the $\Ext^0 \simeq \Hom$ equivalence: plain, additive, and $k$-linear. We choose the $k$-linear refinement because it is the one consumed downstream: finiteness of $H^0_{\Module}(F)$ over $k$ is equivalent to finiteness of the Hom group, via transport along a $k$-linear equivalence.
225	\end{remark}
