102	\section{Invertible objects and line bundles}
103	
104	\begin{definition}[Invertible $\mathcal O_X$-module]
105	  \label{def:Modules_Invertible}
106	  An $\mathcal O_X$-module $L$ is \emph{invertible} (or a \emph{line bundle}) if there exists $L' \in X.\mathrm{Modules}$ and an isomorphism $L \otimes_{\mathcal O_X} L' \cong \mathcal O_X$.
107	\end{definition}
108	
109	Equivalently, $L$ is invertible iff it is an invertible object of the symmetric monoidal category $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ in the sense of \texttt{CategoryTheory.MonoidalCategory.Invertible}.
110	
111	This is the substrate that Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle} uses to define $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$. The refinement from the global-sections approximation $\mathrm{CommRing.Pic}\,\Gamma(X, \top)$ to the invertible-objects definition $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X = (\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules})^\times$ was carried out as Phase~C step~C1 in iter-109 (Archon canonical) and is now in place; the universe pinning succeeded against \texttt{Type\,\_} without an intervening $\mathrm{Shrink}$ wrapper, so the C1 definition is the bare $(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules})^\times$. The load-bearing transition of $\mathtt{instIsMonoidal\_W}$ that this refinement induces is disclosed in Remark~\ref{rem:W_IsMonoidal_load_bearing}.
