1	\chapter{The relative Picard functor as an abelian-group-valued presheaf}
2	\label{chap:Picard_FunctorAb}
3	
4	This chapter is the natural successor to Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}. The relative Picard functor of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor} is set-valued; the construction merely forgets the abelian-group structure that the values $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$ carry by definition. To set up Phase~C step~3 (\'etale sheafification) and any future cohomology-of-Picard-presheaf work, we need an abelian-group-valued variant whose values agree on the nose with the set-valued ones.
5	
6	The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and lemma here is auxiliary, supporting Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian} via the same path as Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}.
7	
8	\section{Definition}
9	
10	\begin{definition}[Relative Picard functor, abelian-group valued]
11	  \label{def:Pic_functorAb}
12	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb}
13	  \uses{def:Pic_functor}
14	  Let $C$ be a scheme over $\Spec k$. The \emph{abelian-group-valued relative Picard functor} of $C$ over $k$ is the contravariant functor
15	  \[
16	    \PicardFunctorAb\, C \;\colon\; (\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}} \;\longrightarrow\; \AddCommGrpCat,\qquad
17	    S \;\longmapsto\; \mathtt{AddCommGrpCat.of}\;\bigl(\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)\bigr),
18	  \]
19	  with morphisms induced by the quotient pull-back maps defined in Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}.
20	\end{definition}
21	
22	\begin{remark}
23	  The underlying-set functor of $\PicardFunctorAb\, C$ agrees on the nose with the set-valued Picard functor of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}: Definition~\ref{def:Pic_functor} computes the same group quotient $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$ but discards the group structure. The forget-and-recover natural iso (Definition~\ref{def:PicardFunctorAb_forgetCompare} below) records this. It is needed to transport later results (e.g.\ representability) between the two flavours.
24	\end{remark}
25	
26	\section{Forget-and-recover natural iso}
27	
28	\begin{definition}[$\PicardFunctorAb$ recovers $\PicardFunctor$ along forget]
29	  \label{def:PicardFunctorAb_forgetCompare}
30	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb.forgetCompare}
31	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb, def:Pic_functor}
32	  Let $C$ be a scheme over $\Spec k$. Then there is a natural isomorphism of set-valued functors
33	  \[
34	    \PicardFunctorAb\, C \,\circ\, \forget \AddCommGrpCat \;\cong\; \PicardFunctor\, C
35	  \]
36	  in $(\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}} \to \mathrm{Set}$.
37	\end{definition}
38	
39	\begin{proof}
40	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb, def:Pic_functor}
41	  Both sides have the same object at $S \in (\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}}$ --- the quotient set $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$ --- and the same map on morphisms --- the quotient pull-back. The additive wrapper is type-equal to its underlying multiplicative quotient, so the two functors agree on the nose at the underlying-type level. The natural iso is therefore the identity natural transformation in disguise.
42	\end{proof}
43	
44	\begin{lemma}[Forget-evaluation simp lemma]
45	  \label{lem:PicardFunctorAb_forget_obj}
46	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb_forget_obj}
47	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb, def:PicardFunctorAb_forgetCompare}
48	  For every $S \in (\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}}$,
49	  \[
50	    (\forget\,\AddCommGrpCat).\mathrm{obj}\,\bigl((\PicardFunctorAb\, C).\mathrm{obj}\,S\bigr) \;=\; (\PicardFunctor\, C).\mathrm{obj}\,S.
51	  \]
52	\end{lemma}
53	
54	\begin{proof}
55	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb, def:PicardFunctorAb_forgetCompare}
56	  Definitionally true: both sides are the underlying carrier of the quotient $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$.
57	\end{proof}
58	
59	\section{\'Etale sheafification}
60	
61	The \'etale-sheafified relative Picard functor is built on top of $\PicardFunctorAb$. The Mathlib gap that previously blocked this (sheafification for the \'etale topology over $\Spec k$ valued in $\AddCommGrpCat$) closed in current Mathlib. Post-iter-109 (cascading from the C1 promotion of $\mathrm{LineBundle}$ in Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}), the codomain of $\PicardFunctorAb$ has bumped from $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u\}$ to $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u+1\}$: the C1 refactor pushed $\Pic\,X$ into $\mathrm{Type}\,(u+1)$, $\PicardFunctor$ inherited the bump (landing in $\mathrm{Type}\,(u+1)$ rather than $\mathrm{Type}\,u$), and $\PicardFunctorAb$ in turn followed (landing in $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u+1\}$ rather than $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u\}$). The post-iter-109 codomain $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u+1\}$ already matches the value-universe at which Mathlib's $\mathrm{HasSheafify}$ instance for the \'etale topology over $\Spec k$ is inferable, so the universe-pinning gymnastic that the pre-iter-109 framing required (post-composing with the natural universe lift $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u\} \to \AddCommGrpCat.\{u+1\}$) is no longer needed: the body of $\mathrm{etaleSheafified}$ simplifies by one functor composition.
62	
63	\begin{definition}[\'Etale-sheafified relative Picard functor]
64	  \label{def:PicardFunctorAb_etaleSheafified}
65	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb.etaleSheafified}
66	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb}
67	  Let $C$ be a scheme over $\Spec k$. The \emph{\'etale-sheafified relative Picard functor} of $C$ over $k$ is the \'etale sheaf on $\Sch_k$ obtained by sheafifying $\PicardFunctorAb\, C$ directly. Post-iter-109 (cascading from the C1 promotion of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}), $\PicardFunctorAb\, C$ already lands in $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u+1\}$ --- the value-universe at which the \'etale-topology sheafification over $\Spec k$ is inferable in current Mathlib --- so the pre-iter-109 universe-lift composition $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u\} \to \AddCommGrpCat.\{u+1\}$ that bridged the iter-004 codomain $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u\}$ to that value-universe is no longer needed.
68	\end{definition}
69	
70	\begin{proof}
71	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb}
72	  Apply the Mathlib sheafification left-adjoint to $\PicardFunctorAb\, C$ directly. The two sheafification instances are inferable in current Mathlib for the \'etale topology over $\Spec k$ valued in $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u+1\}$, so sheafification types out without extra hypotheses on the (post-iter-109) codomain $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u+1\}$ of $\PicardFunctorAb$ --- no universe-lift composition is interposed.
73	\end{proof}
74	
75	\section{Use in the project}
76	
77	Definitions~\ref{def:Pic_functorAb} and~\ref{def:PicardFunctorAb_etaleSheafified} set up the codomain needed for:
78	
79	\begin{itemize}
80	  \item The \'etale-sheafified version of the relative Picard functor of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}: the input shape required by Grothendieck's representability machinery is a sheaf for the \'etale topology, not a presheaf.
81	  \item Comparison with the Jacobian's $\Pic^0$ as a group scheme: the connected-component-of-identity of the representing scheme is a group object in $\Sch_k$.
82	  \item Direct definition of $H^n$-of-the-Picard-presheaf if a future iteration wants to expose it as a derived functor.
83	\end{itemize}
84	
85	The representability theorem~\ref{thm:Pic_representable} of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor} carries over verbatim once the \'etale sheafification of $\PicardFunctorAb$ has been constructed; the four Jacobian sorries are the same as before, and the remaining gating obstruction for representability is the line-bundle refinement of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}. This chapter does \emph{not} add a representability theorem of its own --- the present chapter is the codomain change plus the \'etale sheafification.
